  "doc_id": "36016",
  "text": "Although the causes of obesity among children are multilayered, data suggest that by toddlerhood, many children are at risk because of overeating. Thus, preventive feeding interventions are especially necessary during age-appropriate transition to solid foods. Mothers' misinterpretation of infant feeding cues, the use of controlling feeding styles, and poor feeding practices can affect infants' ability to regulate food intake [CITATION_1] . Although mothers have some knowledge about infant nutrition and feeding cues as infants transition from human milk/ formula-based diets to solid foods, they continue to rely on inappropriate indicators of satiation, such as infants' sleeping through the night and advice from extended family members [CITATION_2] . Our study focuses on the promotion of healthy infant feeding practices in reducing the risk of early onset of childhood obesity.",
